block content

    section.section--theories
        .wrap--content

            h2.heading--2.
                While the exact cause of binge eating disorder (B.E.D.) is unknown,

            h1.heading--1.
                Research suggests B.E.D. may have a neurobiological basis with genetic and environmental risk factors

            h2.heading--2.
                These prevailing theories may support a neurobiological basis for !{BED}

            .row.brain

                .icon.is--vc

                h4.heading--4.
                    Reward center and impulsivity dysregulation theory
                p.
                    Adults with !{BED} have shown reduced activity in impulse control&ndash;related regions of the brain#[sup 1-4]

            .row.neuron

                .icon.is--vc

                h4.heading--4.
                    Neurotransmitter dysregulation theory
                p.
                    Dopamine signaling converts sensory stimuli into processes that may generate or enhance “wanting” of a particular food#[sup 5-7]

            .row.neuron-closeup

                .icon.is--vc

                h4.heading--4.
                    Endogenous μ-opioid signaling dysfunction theory
                p.
                    Opioid signaling converts sensory stimuli into processes that generate or enhance “liking” of a particular food#[sup 8-11]

    section.section--factors
        .wrap--content

            h1.heading--1.
                Research also suggests these possible risk factors for !{BED}

            .row.dna

                .icon.is--vc

                h4.heading--4.
                    Genetics

                ul.square
                    li
                        | !{BED} appears to run in families, which may reflect additive genetic influences#[sup 12]
                    li
                        | Genetic differences in neurobiological components of the brain's reward center have been observed#[sup 8,13]

            .row.people

                .icon.is--vc

                h4.heading--4.
                    Environmental and social influences

                ul.square
                    li
                        | In a case-controlled retrospective assessment of 162 women with !{BED}, stressful life events were reported more frequently in the year preceding !{BED} onset than in non-!{BED} controls#[sup 5]
                    li
                        | In a nationally representative survey of 5,702 adults, of the men (n=30) and women (n=75) who reported having !{BED}, 98% and 90%, respectively, reported experiencing some form of trauma*#[sup 14]

            p(data-note="*").footnote.
                Exposure to events such as combat, life-threatening accidents, a major disaster, or physical or sexual assault.#[sup 14]

